@node	5.1.5, 5.2, Chapter 5, 5.1
@subsection Instruction Summary

A controller instruction in our register-machine language has one of the
following forms, where each @math{{⟨\kern0.06em input_i⟩}} is either 
@code{(reg ⟨@var{register-name}⟩)} or @code{(const ⟨@var{constant-value}⟩)}.  
These instructions were introduced in @ref{5.1.1}:

@lisp
(assign ⟨@var{register-name}⟩ (reg ⟨@var{register-name}⟩))
(assign ⟨@var{register-name}⟩ 
        (const ⟨@var{constant-value}⟩))
(assign ⟨@var{register-name}⟩ 
        (op ⟨@var{operation-name}⟩) 
        ⟨@var{input₁}⟩ @r{…} ⟨@var{inputₙ}⟩)
(perform (op ⟨@var{operation-name}⟩) 
         ⟨@var{input₁}⟩ 
         @r{…} 
         ⟨@var{inputₙ}⟩)
(test (op ⟨@var{operation-name}⟩) 
      ⟨@var{input₁}⟩ 
      @r{…} 
      ⟨@var{inputₙ}⟩)
(branch (label ⟨@var{label-name}⟩))
(goto (label ⟨@var{label-name}⟩))
@end lisp

@noindent
The use of registers to hold labels was introduced in @ref{5.1.3}:

@lisp
(assign ⟨@var{register-name}⟩ (label ⟨@var{label-name}⟩))
(goto (reg ⟨@var{register-name}⟩))
@end lisp

@noindent
Instructions to use the stack were introduced in @ref{5.1.4}:

@lisp
(save ⟨@var{register-name}⟩)
(restore ⟨@var{register-name}⟩)
@end lisp

@noindent
The only kind of @code{⟨}@var{constant-value}@code{⟩} we have seen so far is a number,
but later we will use strings, symbols, and lists.
For example,@*
@code{(const "abc")} is the string @code{"abc"},@*
@code{(const abc)} is the symbol @code{abc},@*
@code{(const (a b c))} is the list @code{(a b c)},@*
and @code{(const ())} is the empty list.

